What is a Map?
A map is a collection of keyâ€“value pairs.
ğŸ‘‰ Similar to dictionary / hash map.

m := make(map[string]int)

m := map[string]int{
    "a": 1,
    "b": 2,
}

- Nil map
var m map[string]int

- Zero Value of Map (INTERVIEW)
    Zero value = nil
    Reading is allowed
    Writing causes panic

var m map[string]int
fmt.Println(m["a"]) // 0
m["a"] = 1          // âŒ panic

- Accessing Values
  v := m["a"]

- Comma OK Idiom (VERY IMPORTANT)
  v, ok := m["a"]
  ok == true â†’ key exists
  ok == false â†’ key does not exist

- Updating & Adding
  m["a"] = 10
  âœ” Same syntax for add & update.

- Deleting Key
  delete(m, "a")
  âœ” Safe even if key doesnâ€™t exist.

- Looping Over Map
  for k, v := range m {
    fmt.Println(k, v)
  }
Order is NOT guaranteed.

- Map is Reference Type (VERY IMPORTANT)
  m1 := map[string]int{"a": 1}
  m2 := m1
  m2["a"] = 100
  
  fmt.Println(m1["a"]) // 100
âœ” No copy on assignment.

- Passing Map to Function
  func update(m map[string]int) {
      m["a"] = 50
  }
âœ” Original map modified.

- Map with Struct Values
  type User struct {
      Name string
  }
  
  users := map[int]User{
      1: {Name: "Go"},
  }
Cannot modify struct field directly:
users[1].Name = "Lang" // âŒ

âœ” Fix:
  u := users[1]
  u.Name = "Lang"
  users[1] = u

- Map with Slice Values
  m := map[string][]int{}
  m["a"] = append(m["a"], 1)
  âœ” Works even if key doesnâ€™t exist.
  

- Map Keys Rules (INTERVIEW)
  âœ” Keys must be comparable:
  int
  string
  bool
  structs (with comparable fields)
  
âŒ Invalid keys:
  slice
  map
  function

- Map Comparison
Cannot compare maps directly:
m1 == m2 // âŒ
âœ” Only compare with nil.

- Concurrency (VERY IMPORTANT)
  âŒ Map is NOT thread-safe
fatal error: concurrent map writes

âœ” Solutions:
sync.Mutex
sync.Map

Map Capacity (Performance Tip)
m := make(map[string]int, 1000)
âœ” Reduces rehashing.

A map in Go is a reference-type data structure that stores unordered keyâ€“value pairs, where keys must be comparable and the zero value is nil.



















